@Tutorial(time: 25) {
    @Intro(title: "Replace Subtrees with Witnesses") {
        Cambium trees are persistent: there is no in-place mutation.
        `SharedSyntaxTree.replacing(_:with:context:)` produces a *new*
        tree that shares as much green storage with
        the old as possible, and returns a
        ``CambiumCore/ReplacementWitness`` describing the structural
        change.

        In this tutorial you build a constant-folding pass on top of
        `replacing`. Each iteration finds one foldable expression,
        evaluates it, builds a literal subtree, splices it in, and
        records the witness. Tutorial 9 shows how analysis caches use
        those witnesses to translate per-node values across edits
        without re-evaluating untouched subtrees.
    }

    @Section(title: "Structural types") {
        @ContentAndMedia {
            A fold pass produces a sequence of `FoldStep` records â€”
            one per replacement â€” each carrying the witness that
            described the change. The witness is `Sendable` and
            `Copyable`, so consumers can hold it past the borrow
            scope and inspect it later.
        }

        @Steps {
            @Step {
                Define `FoldStep`, `FoldReport`, and the internal
                `FoldCandidate` / `FoldLiteral` value types.
                `FoldStep.witness` and `FoldStep.newTree` are the
                Cambium-typed fields; everything else is fold-specific
                bookkeeping.

                @Code(name: "CalculatorFold.swift", file: "07-fold-01-types.swift")
            }
        }
    }

    @Section(title: "Find a foldable expression in post-order") {
        @ContentAndMedia {
            The fold engine walks the tree in *post-order*: children
            visited before their parents. ``CambiumCore/SyntaxNodeCursor/walkPreorder(_:)``
            emits both `.enter` and `.leave` events; acting on
            `.leave` gives us post-order traversal without an extra
            stack.

            A node is foldable when every direct operand is already a
            literal â€” at that point we can evaluate it with the
            evaluator from Tutorial 6.
        }

        @Steps {
            @Step {
                Add `firstFoldCandidate(in:)`. It walks the tree on
                `.leave` events, asks `evaluatedValue(for:)` whether
                the node's operands are literals, and snapshots the
                first candidate. The walk is borrowed; the candidate
                materializes an owned `SyntaxNodeHandle`,
                `SyntaxNodePath`, and source text once it has decided
                to commit.

                @Code(name: "CalculatorFold.swift", file: "07-fold-02-candidate.swift")
            }
        }
    }

    @Section(title: "Build a replacement and splice it in") {
        @ContentAndMedia {
            `SharedSyntaxTree.replacing(_:with:context:)` takes an
            owned handle for the node to replace, a
            ``CambiumCore/ResolvedGreenNode`` (a green subtree paired
            with its resolver), and a ``CambiumBuilder/GreenTreeContext``
            whose interner shares the target tree's namespace.

            Reusing the source tree's context is what lets the splice
            take ``CambiumBuilder/SubtreeReuseOutcome/direct`` rather
            than re-interning every dynamic token. The replacement's
            green storage is shared into the new tree, while the rest
            of the old tree is structurally shared too â€” only the
            ancestors of the replaced node get rebuilt.
        }

        @Steps {
            @Step {
                Add `applyFold`. The pattern is: build the replacement
                with a fresh ``CambiumBuilder/GreenTreeBuilder`` bound
                to the supplied context, finish it into a
                ``CambiumCore/ResolvedGreenNode``, then call
                `tree.replacing(...)` and capture the witness.

                The function is `consuming` over the context and hands
                the next context back inside `FoldApplyOutput` â€”
                Swift tuples cannot yet hold `~Copyable` values, so a
                small carrier struct fills in.

                @Code(name: "CalculatorFold.swift", file: "07-fold-03-replace.swift")
            }
        }
    }

    @Section(title: "Iterate to a fixed point") {
        @ContentAndMedia {
            One fold pass replaces one expression. A real fold drives
            the pass in a loop until no candidate remains; each
            iteration's output context becomes the next iteration's
            input, so green-node cache hits and namespace identity
            carry across.
        }

        @Steps {
            @Step {
                Add the public `foldCalculatorTree` driver. The loop
                threads the evolving tree and the
                ``CambiumBuilder/GreenTreeContext`` through every
                iteration. By the time the loop exits, `steps`
                contains one entry per replacement and the final
                tree is fully folded.

                @Code(name: "CalculatorFold.swift", file: "07-fold-04-loop.swift")
            }
        }
    }

    @Section(title: "Inspect the witness") {
        @ContentAndMedia {
            The point of the witness is to translate references
            across the change. ``CambiumCore/ReplacementWitness/classify(path:)``
            takes a path that addressed a node in the *old* tree and
            returns a ``CambiumCore/ReplacementOutcome`` saying what
            happened to that node.
        }

        @Steps {
            @Step {
                Walk through the four `ReplacementOutcome` cases for a
                couple of paths from each fold step. For paths
                outside the replaced region you get `.unchanged`; for
                the replaced node itself you get `.replacedRoot` with
                the new green subtree.

                Tutorial 9 puts this to use: the analysis cache
                translates a node's old `SyntaxNodeIdentity` through
                `classify(path:)` so that every entry whose path
                still resolves to a corresponding new-tree node keeps
                its cached value.

                @Code(name: "WitnessDemo.swift", file: "07-witness-inspect.swift")
            }
        }
    }

    @Assessments {
        @MultipleChoice {
            Why must `applyFold` build the replacement subtree using a
            ``CambiumBuilder/GreenTreeContext`` that shares the target
            tree's namespace?

            @Choice(isCorrect: false) {
                Otherwise the splice would crash at runtime.

                @Justification(reaction: "Try again") {
                    The splice still succeeds â€” Cambium handles
                    cross-namespace splices by remapping. The reason
                    is performance, not correctness.
                }
            }

            @Choice(isCorrect: true) {
                A cross-namespace splice falls into the
                ``CambiumBuilder/SubtreeReuseOutcome/remapped`` path,
                which re-interns every dynamic token. Same-namespace
                splices take ``CambiumBuilder/SubtreeReuseOutcome/direct``
                â€” green-node identity is preserved.

                @Justification(reaction: "That's right") {
                    Sharing the context is what lets the fold
                    iteratively reuse green storage across passes
                    instead of rebuilding from scratch.
                }
            }

            @Choice(isCorrect: false) {
                Cambium requires a single global context per process.

                @Justification(reaction: "Try again") {
                    Many contexts can coexist. Each carries its own
                    namespace; the constraint is that splices benefit
                    from matching namespaces.
                }
            }
        }

        @MultipleChoice {
            What does `ReplacementOutcome.unchanged` guarantee about
            the path's node in the new tree?

            @Choice(isCorrect: false) {
                The node has the same `SyntaxNodeIdentity` as in the
                old tree.

                @Justification(reaction: "Try again") {
                    `SyntaxNodeIdentity` is per-tree. The new tree
                    has a fresh `TreeID`, so identities differ even
                    when the node is structurally unchanged.
                }
            }

            @Choice(isCorrect: true) {
                The node is structurally preserved â€” the same path
                resolves to a node with the same green storage as in
                the old tree.

                @Justification(reaction: "That's right") {
                    Persistent storage is the mechanism: the
                    unreplaced subtrees share green nodes between old
                    and new. Identity tracking that wants to follow
                    nodes across the edit walks the path again on the
                    new tree.
                }
            }

            @Choice(isCorrect: false) {
                The node is in the same byte range as before.

                @Justification(reaction: "Try again") {
                    Replacing a subtree changes byte offsets for
                    everything to its right. `.unchanged` is about
                    structural preservation, not byte coordinates.
                }
            }
        }
    }
}
